1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:05,000
Claude Code is powerful out of the box.
But every session starts fresh.

2
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:09,000
It doesn't remember your team's rules,
your project's architecture,

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,000
or the mistakes it made yesterday.
ClaudeOS fixes that.

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:19,000
Four files load into every session automatically.
Your team's build commands and architecture.

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:24,500
Your personal review style and preferences.
Permission auto-approvals so Claude doesn't

6
00:00:24,500 --> 00:00:29,500
ask for confirmation on safe commands.
And a living memory of patterns learned

7
00:00:29,500 --> 00:00:34,000
across hundreds of sessions.
Plus 22 topic files,

8
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,500
auto-synced from Confluence every 24 hours.

9
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,500
Claude learns from its mistakes.
When it tries to use the gh CLI,

10
00:00:43,500 --> 00:00:48,000
which isn't installed, that gets logged.
After multiple occurrences across sessions,

11
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:52,500
the pattern gets recognized
and promoted to a permanent rule.

12
00:00:52,500 --> 00:00:57,000
From that point on,
Claude never makes that mistake again.

13
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:02,000
The progression is: session log,
to recognized pattern, to permanent rule.

14
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,500
Five scheduled scripts
replace the manual loop.

15
00:01:07,500 --> 00:01:12,000
Logging every hour. Distilling patterns daily.
Promoting rules weekly.

16
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:18,500
Syncing Confluence and Notion docs automatically.
All running on launchd, across two repos.
Ten agents total.

17
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:23,500
Custom slash commands turn
multi-step workflows into one-liners.

18
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:28,000
Type slash review with a ticket number,
and Claude fetches the branch,

19
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:32,500
diffs every file, runs regression scans,
and posts a categorized review

20
00:01:32,500 --> 00:01:38,000
directly on the pull request.
Here's a real review it posted on Bitbucket.

21
00:01:38,500 --> 00:01:43,500
Setting up a new repo takes one command.
Bootstrap copies your templates,

22
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:48,500
slash commands, automation scripts,
and starter memory.

23
00:01:48,500 --> 00:01:53,500
Checkpoint saves changes back.
Your conventions travel with you across every project.

24
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:58,000
The automation runs for about
four dollars a week.

25
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:01,000
Each script is budget-capped
so there are no surprises.
